<section xml:id="sum_and_difference_formulas">
  <title>Sum and Difference Formulas</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In ***********
    </p>
      <!-- In <xref ref="right_triangle_trigonometry"/>,  -->

    <p>
      In Section ***********, we used right triangles to determine the deviation of a waʻa (canoe) from its course based on the angle of deviation. If a waʻa sails for 120 nautical miles (NM), we were able to calculate the deviation from its course using right triangles to get the equation:
      <me>
        \mbox{deviation} = (120\mbox{ NM})\cdot\sin(\theta)
      </me>.        
    </p>
    <image xml:id="deviation-sum-formula" width="100%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=7]
        \node[above,yshift=2] at (0,0) {start};
        \node[above right] at (11.25:1.2) {end};
        \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth] (0,0) -- (11.25:1.2) node[midway,sloped,above] {120 NM};
        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (1.17694233648,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {reference course};
        \draw[dashed] (1.17694233648,0) -- (1.17694233648,0.234108386419) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1] {deviation};
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.3)]0,0) arc (0:11.25:0.3) node[midway,right,xshift=12,yshift=2] {$\theta$};
        \draw ([shift=(11.25:-0.1)]0,0) pic {waa-top={waacolor}{-78.75}{0.1}};
        \draw (1.17694233648-0.06,0) -- (1.11694233648,0.06) -- (1.17694233648,0.06);\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>    
    <p>
      Before setting sail, a voyager studies a table listing the deviation distances corresponding to different houses of deviation. It's crucial to understand that while adding angles may yield a third angle, adding their corresponding deviations will not accurately determine the total deviation. In other words:
      <me>
        \sin(\alpha) + \sin(\beta) \neq \sin(\alpha + \beta)
      </me>
      for some angles of deviation <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      To illustrate this, let's calculate the deviation distances for 1, 2, and 3 houses respectively. Using the given formula, we have:
      <md>
        <mrow>120 \sin(1 \mbox{ house}) \amp = 120 \sin(11.25^{\circ}) \approx 23.4 \mbox{ NM}</mrow>
        <mrow>120 \sin(2 \mbox{ houses})\amp = 120 \sin(22.5^{\circ}) \approx 45.9 \mbox{ NM}</mrow>
        <mrow>120 \sin(3 \mbox{ houses}) \amp = 120 \sin(33.75^{\circ}) \approx 66.7 \mbox{ NM}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      However,
      <me>
        120 \sin(1 \mbox{ house}) + 120 \sin(2 \mbox{ houses}) \approx 23.4 + 45.9 \mbox{ NM} \approx 69.3 \mbox{ NM}
      </me>,
      which is not 66.7 NM.        
    </p>
    <p>
      hese calculations demonstrate that the deviation distances for multiple houses cannot be determined by simply adding individual deviations, highlighting the importance of understanding trigonometric principles for accurate navigation. In this section, we will explore formulas for the addition and subtraction of angles in trigonometric functions.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Sum and Difference Formulas</title><idx><h>sum and difference formulas</h></idx>
    <definition xml:id="def-sum-diff-cosine">
      <title>Sum and Difference Formulas for Cosine</title><idx><h>Sum and Difference Formulas</h><h>for Cosine</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
            <mrow>\cos(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        First we will prove the Difference Formula for Cosine
        <me>
          \cos(\alpha-\beta)=\cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We begin by considering two points on the unit circle. Point <m>P</m> is at an angle of <m>\beta</m> in standard position with coordinates <m>(\cos\beta,\sin\beta)</m> and point <m>Q</m> is at an angle of <m>\alpha</m> in standard position with coordinates <m>(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha)</m>.
      </p>
      <image xml:id="fig-cos-diff-proof1">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
          \draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
          \node at (-0.1,-0.1) {\(O\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (115:1) node[black,above,xshift=-0.2cm]{\(Q(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha)\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (40:1) node[black,right,xshift=0.2cm]{\(P(\cos\beta,\sin\beta)\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,red] (115:1) -- (40:1);
          \filldraw (115:1cm) circle(1pt);
          \filldraw (40:1cm) circle(1pt);
          \filldraw (0,0) circle(1pt);
          \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.2cm) arc (0:115:0.2cm) node[midway, above,yshift=0.1cm,xshift=-0.1cm] {\(\alpha\)};
          \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.4cm) arc (0:40:0.4cm) node[midway, right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\beta\)};
          \draw[-stealth, line width=1.25pt] (40:0.5cm) arc (40:115:0.5cm) node[midway, above,xshift=0.2cm] {\(\alpha-\beta\)};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        We use the Distance Formula to calculate the distance between <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> to get
        <md>
          <mrow>d(P,Q)\amp = \sqrt{(\cos\alpha-\cos\beta)^2+(\sin\alpha-\sin\beta)^2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\cos^2\alpha-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta+\cos^2\beta+\sin^2\alpha-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta+\sin^2\beta}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{(\cos^2\alpha+\sin^2\alpha)+(\cos^2\beta+\sin^2\beta)-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Then by the Pythagorean Identify,
        <md>
          <mrow>d(P,Q) \amp = \sqrt{1+1-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{2-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, consider two additional points on a second unit circle.
        Point <m>A</m> has coordinates at <m>(1,0)</m> and Point <m>B</m> is at an angle of
        <m>\alpha-\beta</m> in standard position with coordinates <m>(\cos(\alpha-\beta),\sin(\alpha-\beta))</m>.
      </p>
      <image xml:id="fig-cos-diff-proof2">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
          \draw (0,0) circle (1);
          \node at (-0.1,-0.1) {\(O\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[black,above,xshift=15,yshift=1]{\(A(1,0)\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (75:1) node[black,right,xshift=4,yshift=2]{\(B(\cos(\alpha-\beta),\sin(\alpha-\beta))\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt,red] (1,0) -- (75:1);
          \filldraw (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
          \filldraw (75:1cm) circle(1pt);
          \filldraw (0,0) circle(1pt);
          \draw[-stealth,line width=1.25pt] (0:0.2cm) arc (0:75:0.2cm) node[midway, right,xshift=0.1cm] {\(\alpha-\beta\)};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        The distance between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is
        <md>
          <mrow>d(A,B)\amp = \sqrt{(\cos(\alpha-\beta)-1)^2+(\sin(\alpha-\beta)-0)^2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{\cos^2(\alpha-\beta)-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)+1+\sin^2(\alpha-\beta)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{(\cos^2(\alpha-\beta)+\sin^2(\alpha-\beta))-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)+1}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{1-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)+1}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{2-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Note that since <m>OP</m>, <m>OQ</m>, <m>OA</m>, and <m>OB</m> are lines from the center to points on the unit circle,
        they are congruent and have length of 1. Also note that <m>\angle POB=\angle AOB=\alpha-\beta</m>. Then since two sides and the included angle of <m>\Delta OPQ</m> and <m>\Delta OAB</m> are equivalent, we can conclude by side-angle-side theorem (SAS) that the two triangles are congruent. Thus, <m>d(PQ)=d(AB)</m>. Substituting our results for <m>d(P,Q)</m> and <m>d(A,B)</m> we get
        <md>
          <mrow>d(PQ)\amp = d(AB)</mrow>
          <mrow>\sqrt{2-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta}\amp = \sqrt{2-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)}</mrow>
          <mrow>2-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta\amp = 2-2\cos(\alpha-\beta)</mrow>
          <mrow>-2\cos\alpha\cos\beta-2\sin\alpha\sin\beta\amp = -2\cos(\alpha-\beta)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Dividing both sides by -2 we arrive at the Difference Formula for Cosine
        <me>
          \cos\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta=\cos(\alpha-\beta)
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        To prove the Sum Formula for Cosine, replace <m>\beta</m> with <m>-\beta</m> in the Difference Formula and use the Even-Odd Identities where <m>\sin(-\beta)=-\sin\beta</m> and <m>\cos(-\beta)=\cos\beta</m> to get
        <md>
          <mrow>\cos\alpha\cos(-\beta)+\sin\alpha\sin(-\beta)\amp = \cos(\alpha-(-\beta))</mrow>
          <mrow>\cos\alpha\cos(\beta)+\sin\alpha(-\sin\beta)\amp = \cos(\alpha+\beta)</mrow>
          <mrow>\cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta\amp = \cos(\alpha+\beta)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </proof>
    
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of <m>\cos105^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First note that <m>105^{\circ}=60^{\circ}+45^{\circ}</m>. Now, using the Sum Formula for Cosine,
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos105^{\circ}\amp = \cos(60^{\circ}+45^{\circ})</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \cos60^{\circ}\cos45^{\circ}-\sin60^{\circ}\sin45^{\circ}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{4}\left(\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{6}\right)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of <m>\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{\pi}{6}\right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Using the Difference Formula for Cosine we get
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{\pi}{6}\right)\amp = \cos\frac{\pi}{4}\cos\frac{\pi}{6}+\sin\frac{\pi}{4}\sin\frac{\pi}{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}+\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{4}\left(\sqrt{6}+\sqrt{2}\right)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of the expression <m>\cos25^{\circ}\cos35^{\circ}-\sin25^{\circ}\sin35^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Notice this expression is the Sum Formula for Cosine with <m>\alpha=25^{\circ}</m> and <m>\beta=35^{\circ}</m>. So
          <me>
            \cos25^{\circ}\cos35^{\circ}-\sin25^{\circ}\sin35^{\circ}=\cos(25^{\circ}+35^{\circ})=\cos60^{\circ}=\frac{1}{2}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-sum-diff-sine">
      <title>Sum and Difference Formulas for Sine</title><idx><h>Sum and Difference Formulas</h><h>for Sine</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
            <mrow>\sin(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta-\cos\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We will prove the Sum Formula for Sine in <xref ref="sum-formula-sine-proof"/>
      and the Difference Formula can be established using the Even-Odd Identities.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="ex-cofunction-identity-cos">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the Difference Formula for Sine to establish the identity <m>\cos\theta=\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To establish an identity, we will start from one side of the equality and use properties to end up with the expression on the other side of the equality. So,
          <me>
            \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)=\sin\frac{\pi}{2}\cos\theta-\cos\frac{\pi}{2}\sin\theta=1\cdot\cos\theta-0\cdot\sin\theta=\cos\theta
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Visually, we have <m>\cos\theta=\frac{x}{r}=\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</m>:
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-diff-formula-cofunction">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
            \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway,below]{x};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway,right]{y};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (4,3) -- (0,0) node[midway,above]{r};
            \draw (0:1) arc (0:36.8698976458:1) node[midway, left,xshift=12,yshift=4] {\(\theta\)};
            \draw (36.8698976458:4) arc (216.869897646:270:1) node[midway, left,xshift=8,yshift=-8] {\(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\)};
            \draw (3.4,0) -- (3.4,0.6) -- (4,0.6);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given <m>\sin\alpha=-\frac{12}{13}</m>, with <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}\lt \alpha\lt 2\pi</m> and <m>\cos\beta=-\frac{3}{5}</m>, with <m>\frac{\pi}{2}\lt \beta\lt \pi</m>, find the exact value of <m>\sin(\alpha+\beta)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The Sum Formula for Sine gives us
          <me>
            \sin(\alpha+\beta)=\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          At this moment, we do not know the exact values of <m>\cos\alpha</m> and <m>\sin\beta</m> but we can compute them.
        </p>
        <p>
          Given <m>\sin\alpha=-\frac{12}{13}</m> with <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}\lt \alpha\lt 2\pi</m> and <m>\cos\beta=-\frac{3}{5}</m> with <m>\frac{\pi}{2}\lt \beta\lt \pi</m>, we can draw the following triangles associated with <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>, respectively:
        </p>
        <image xml:id="ex-sum-formula1">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
            \draw (-0.5,0)--(5.5,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,0.5)--(0,-13.5) node[below]{\(y\)};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (5,0) node[midway,above]{x};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (5,0) -- (5,-12) node[midway,right]{-12};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (5,-12) -- (0,0) node[midway,above,xshift=5]{13};
            \draw (0:1) arc (0:-67.380135052:1) node[midway, right,xshift=3,yshift=-2] {\(\alpha\)};
            \draw (4.2,0) -- (4.2,-0.8) -- (5,-0.8);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <image xml:id="ex-sum-formula2">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (-3.5,0)--(0.5,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-0.5)--(0,4.5) node[above]{\(y\)};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (0,0) -- (-3,0) node[midway,below]{-3};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (-3,0) -- (-3,4) node[midway,left]{y};
            \draw[line width=1pt] (-3,4) -- (0,0) node[midway,above,xshift=3]{5};
            \draw (126.869897646:1) arc (126.869897646:180:1) node[midway, left,xshift=-1,yshift=4] {\(\beta\)};
            \draw (-2.6,0) -- (-2.6,0.4) -- (-3,0.4);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          Next, using the Pythagorean Theorem, we solve for the missing sides on the triangles
          <md>
            <mrow>x^2+(-12)^2\amp = 13^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x+144\amp = 169</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2\amp = 25</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp = 5</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus we get
          <me>
            \cos\alpha=\frac{5}{13}
          </me>
          <md>
            <mrow>(-3)^2+y^2\amp = 5^2</mrow>
            <mrow>9+y^2\amp = 25</mrow>
            <mrow>y^2\amp = 16</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp = 4</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus we get
          <me>
            \sin\beta=-\frac{4}{5}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          We now have all the information needed to proceed.
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \left(-\frac{12}{13}\right)\left(-\frac{3}{5}\right)+\left(\frac{5}{13}\right)\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{36}{65}+\frac{20}{65}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{56}{65}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Notice we did not have to know the values of <m>\alpha</m> or <m>\beta</m> to do this example.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-sum-diff-tangent">
      <title>Sum and Difference Formulas for Tangent</title><idx><h>Sum and Difference Formulas</h><h>for Tangent</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\tan(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \frac{\tan\alpha+\tan\beta}{1-\tan\alpha\tan\beta}</mrow>
            <mrow>\tan(\alpha-\beta)\amp = \frac{\tan\alpha-\tan\beta}{1-\tan\alpha\tan\beta}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Recall that <m>\tan\theta=\frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}</m> as long as <m>\cos\theta\neq0</m>. Using this fact, and our new formulas for the sum of sine and cosine, we get
        <md>
          <mrow>\tan(\alpha+\beta)\amp = \frac{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}{\cos(\alpha+\beta)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\dfrac{\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}{\dfrac{\cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta}{\cancel{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}\cdot\frac{\cancel{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\dfrac{\sin\alpha\cancel{\cos\beta}}{\cos\alpha\cancel{\cos\beta}}+\dfrac{\cancel{\cos\alpha}\sin\beta}{\cancel{\cos\alpha}\cos\beta}}{\dfrac{\cancel{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}{\cancel{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}-\dfrac{\sin\alpha\sin\beta}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\dfrac{\sin\alpha}{\cos\alpha}+\dfrac{\sin\beta}{\cos\beta}}{1-\dfrac{\sin\alpha}{\cos\alpha}\dfrac{\sin\beta}{\cos\beta}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{\tan\alpha+\tan\beta}{1-\tan\alpha\tan\beta}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        The difference formula can be established using the Even-Odd Identities.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of <m>\tan\left(\frac{3\pi}{4}+\frac{\pi}{6}\right)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Using the sum formula for tangent, we get
          <me>
            \tan\left(\frac{3\pi}{4}+\frac{\pi}{6}\right)=\frac{\tan\frac{3\pi}{4}+\tan\frac{\pi}{6}}{1-\tan\frac{3\pi}{4}\tan\frac{\pi}{6}}=\frac{(-1)+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}{1-(-1)\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}=\frac{-1+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}{1+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}=\frac{\frac{-3+\sqrt{3}}{3}}{\frac{3+\sqrt{3}}{3}}=\frac{-3+\sqrt{3}}{3+\sqrt{3}}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Cofunction Identities</title>
    <p>
      Another identity for trigonometric functions is the Cofunction Identities
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-cofunction-identities">
      <title>Cofunction Identities</title><idx><h>cofunction identities</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <em>Cofunction Identities</em> are given below
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\theta\amp =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right) \amp \cos\theta\amp =\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\tan\theta\amp =\cot\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right) \amp \cot\theta\amp =\tan\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\sec\theta\amp =\csc\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right) \amp \csc\theta\amp =\sec\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)</mrow>
      </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        The proof for <m>\sin\theta</m> is given in <xref ref="ex-cofunction-identity-cos">Example</xref>
        and the proof for <m>\cos\theta</m> is given as <xref ref="exer-cofunction-identity-sin">Exercise</xref>.
        The Cofunction Identities for <m>\tan\theta</m> and
        <m>\cot\theta</m> can be found using the Quotient and Cofunction Identities for <m>\csc\theta</m> and
        <m>\sec\theta</m> can be found using the Reciprocal Identities.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Talk about cofunctions and give triangle example. ***************
    </p>
    <example xml:id="sum-formula-sine-proof">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove the Sum Formula for Sine
          <me>
            \sin(\alpha+\beta)=\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We begin by using the cofunction identity
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin(\alpha+\beta)\amp =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-(\alpha+\beta)\right)\amp \amp \mbox{Cofunction Identity}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\cos\left(\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\alpha\right)-\beta\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\alpha\right)\cos\beta+\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\alpha\right)\sin\beta\amp \amp \mbox{Difference Formula for Cosine}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\sin\alpha\sin\beta\amp \amp \mbox{Cofunction Identity}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
